l surfaces in alkaline hydrothermal microcompartments\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent mixing zones; stepwise carboxylative and side-chain functionalization represented in lumped form\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Net mineral-assisted carboxylative side-chain elaboration of an aromatic core to an alpha-keto acid branch point.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is a necessary lumped connector reflecting the literature statement that phenylpyruvate is the key branch point toward phenylalanine and is more ancient than arogenate chemistry (Yoo et al., 2013), while hydrothermal amino-acid-forming energetics are favorable at vent mixing zones (Kitadai, 2015). No direct prebiotic one-step benzene-to-phenylpyruvate synthesis has been demonstrated; therefore this node-connecting transformation is explicitly speculative but included to represent the unresolved bridge identified in the report.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"PAH photoprocessing route from naphthalene-containing ice residues to phenylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"cryogenic ice photolysis precursor stage at 15K followed by surface delivery and warming\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low to 1 atm after deposition\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-activated surface minerals as collection/concentration supports\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"UV/EUV irradiation of PAH + H2O + NH3 ice residues; extraterrestrial-to-surface transfer\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical functionalization and fragmentation of PAH-containing ices yields a residue containing amino acids including phenylalanine upon warming and recovery.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nuevo et al. (2007) showed that UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene in H2O/NH3 ice at 15 K produced phenylalanine as the most abundant aromatic amino acid in the residue. Nuevo et al. (2008) further argued that pre-existing aromatic precursors are required. This route is not terrestrial hydrothermal synthesis but provides a literature-supported complementary source feeding the surface network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidative cleavage relationship between phenylpyruvate and benzaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"trace oxidant-independent bookkeeping of branch relationship under prebiotic interface conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Branch decomposition/cleavage of phenylpyruvate to aromatic aldehyde pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report states that phenylpyruvate connects to benzaldehyde via oxidative cleavage, establishing benzaldehyde as a related branch product. Inclusion here serves network connectivity and aromatic branch accounting; however, exact anoxic prebiotic realization is uncertain and thus this node is a speculative but literature-motivated branch representation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"High-energy conversion of benzaldehyde/acetylene feedstocks to phenylacetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"high-energy irradiative or pyrolytic conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface adsorption and energy dissipation on minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"subaerial geothermal or volcanic setting; UV/discharge-assisted\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic alkynylation/deoxygenative rearrangement contributing to phenylacetylene formation from aromatic aldehyde and acetylene-rich precursor pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann and Miller (1969) demonstrated phenylacetylene formation from simple hydrocarbon/aromatic feedstocks under pyrolysis, discharge, or UV conditions, but did not specifically establish benzaldehyde as a precursor. This reaction is therefore an explicitly speculative connector added only to densify the validated aromatic hub network while remaining consistent with the reported need for high-energy aromatic precursor interconversion (Miller, 1974).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller methane route\",\n      \"description\": \"Methane feeds high-energy aromatic chemistry, generating phenylacetylene, which is converted by H2S hydration and Strecker chemistry to phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller acetylene route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetylene produced hydrothermally or volcanically enters the validated phenylacetylene-H2S-Strecker sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller benzene route\",\n      \"description\": \"Benzene serves as the aromatic precursor for phenylacetylene generation before hydration and Strecker conversion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_int