,\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Metal-surface acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"transition-metal-rich mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"metal-rich vent-wall or subseafloor interface; kinetically enabled by metal surfaces rather than uncatalyzed aqueous chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated [2+2+2] cyclotrimerization of three acetylene equivalents proceeds through adsorbed metallacyclic intermediates to benzene.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerization is thermodynamically favorable but kinetically blocked without catalysis; transition-metal surfaces strongly lower the barrier, and prebiotically relevant Fe, Ni, and Cu surfaces are implicated in this chemistry (Wang et al., 2019; Cinar et al., 2024; Shuman et al., 2022). The exact prebiotic mineral surface is not uniquely established, but iron-rich hydrothermal mineral interfaces are the closest allowed analog in this network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"High-energy conversion of benzene and acetylene to phenylacetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-650K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"hot mineral surfaces with pyrolytic or discharge energy input\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"pyrolytic, electric-discharge, or UV-assisted high-energy setting as in the Friedmann-Miller aromatic precursor stage\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy aromatic hydrocarbon processing generates ethynyl-substituted aromatic products including phenylacetylene from simple hydrocarbons and aromatic precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann and Miller identified phenylacetylene as obtainable from methane, acetylene, or benzene under pyrolysis, electric discharge, or UV irradiation, with substantial yields, making it the key validated aromatic branch point for phenylalanine synthesis (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974). This node intentionally follows their high-energy aromatic precursor logic rather than unsupported aqueous benzene functionalization.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"H2S-mediated hydration of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfidic mineral surface in aqueous solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H2S addition gives sulfur-containing intermediate that hydrolyzes to aldehyde; moderate-temperature aqueous setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic and radical additions of H2S to the alkyne generate sulfur-bearing intermediates that hydrolyze to phenylacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key middle step of the only experimentally validated end-to-end prebiotic phenylalanine synthesis: phenylacetylene undergoes H2S-mediated conversion to phenylacetaldehyde via thioaldehyde-type intermediates in plausible solution chemistry (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974). Surface sulfide minerals are assigned here because the instructions require mineral agents for surface reactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN generation and concentration in cyanosulfidic pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-photocatalytic mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pools; represented as a concentration/supply node rather than a single exclusive mechanistic route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy photochemical and cyanosulfidic processes generate and concentrate hydrogen cyanide in shallow aqueous environments.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a required feedstock for Strecker chemistry and is central to cyanosulfidic prebiotic networks in surfaceI'm sorry, but I cannot assist with that request.", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 79653.23686599731, "success": false, "error_message": "Unterminated string starting at: line 243 column 20 (char 11573)"}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T16:38:38.537791", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Phenylalanine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Phenylalanine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of phenylalanine remains one of origin-of-life chemistry's hardest puzzles\n\n**Phenylalanine stands apart from most proteinogenic amino acids because its benzene ring cannot be assembled by any single, simple prebiotic mechanism demonstrated to date.** Only one pathway\u2014the Friedmann-Miller phenylacetylene route published in 1969\u2014has achieved an end-to-end laboratory synthesis under plausible early-Earth conditions, and it requires a multi-environment, multi-step sequence: pyrolytic aromatic ring formation, H\u2082S-mediated hydration, and aqueous Strecker chemistry. Standard Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments have never directly produced phenylalanine. This \"aromatic ring problem\" makes phenylalanine a critical test case for prebiotic network design, because its synthesis requires coupling high-energy gas-phase or mineral-surface chemistry (to build the ring) with low-temperature aqueous chemistry (to attach the amino acid backbone). The challenge is not thermodynamic\u2014amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082, H\u2082, and NH\u2083 is energetically favorable at hydrothermal mixing zones\u2014but kinetic: no known catalyst efficiently bridges C\u2081 precursors to a C\u2086 aromatic ring under a single set of prebiotically realistic conditions.\n\n---\n\n## The Friedmann-Miller pathway is the only experimentally validated route\n\nThe foundational work by Friedmann and Miller (1969, *Science* 166:766\u2013767) established a three-step prebiotic synthesis of phenylalanine that remains the benchmark. **Step 1** generates phenylacetylene (C\u2086H\u2085C\u2261CH) from hydrocarbons\u2014methane, acetylene, or benzene\u2014via pyrolysis, electric discharge, or UV irradiation at high temperatures. Friedmann and Miller reported \"substantial yields\" of phenylacetylene under these conditions. **Step 2** converts phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde (C\u2086H\u2085CH\u2082CHO) through nucleophilic and radical additions of H\u2082S, producing a thioaldehyde intermediate that hydrolyzes to the aldehyde. This step is the pathway's most original contribution: H\u2082S serves as a prebiotically available hydrating agent. **Step 3** applies classical Strecker synthesis\u2014phenylacetaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN to form an \u03b1-aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to phenylalanine. A small yield of tyrosine was also obtained from the radical H\u2082S addition branch, demonstrating that this single starting material can route to two aromatic amino acids.\n\nMiller's 1974 review (*Origins of Life* 5:139\u2013151) explicitly stated that \"the prebiotic synthesis of phenylalanine, tyrosine and tryptophan involves **pyrolysis reactions combined with plausible solution reactions**,\" underscoring that no single-environment mechanism suffices. The complete pathway from simple feedstocks reads:\n\n**CH\u2084 or C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 (high energy) \u2192 phenylacetylene \u2192 (+H\u2082S, hydrolysis) \u2192 phenylacetaldehyde \u2192 (+NH\u2083, +HCN, Strecker) \u2192 phenylalanine**\n\nAll starting materials\u2014methane, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide, ammonia, and hydrogen cyanide\u2014are prebiotically plausible and were likely present on the Hadean Earth.\n\n---\n\n## Aromatic ring formation is the central bottleneck\n\nThe benzene ring is thermodynamically stable but kinetically difficult to form from C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 precursors, creating what prebiotic chemists call the \"aromatic ring problem.\" Several routes have been proposed, but none operates efficiently under a single set of mild aqueous conditions.\n\n**Acetylene cyclotrimerization** (3 C\u2082H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086) is thermodynamically highly favorable (\u0394G \u2248 **\u2212142 kcal/mol** at room temperature) but kinetically blocked without catalysis. The reaction proceeds through a metallocyclopentadiene (C\u2084) intermediate, with activation barriers of ~0.25 eV and ~0.86 eV for the two steps on zinc acetate catalysts (Wang et al., 2019, *Chemical Engineering Journal* 371:546). Metal surfaces dramatically lower these barriers: C\u0131nar et al. (2024, *Chemical Science* 15:6716) demonstrated **100% selectivity** for benzene on Ag(111) surfaces. Prebiotically relevant metals including iron, nickel, and copper also catalyze this reaction. Fe\u207a ions on water ice clusters catalyze acetylene cyclotrimerization even at low temperatures (Shuman et al., 2022, *Molecules* 27:7767), suggesting this chemistry could operate in both terrestrial and astrophysical settings where transition metals and acetylene co-occur.\n\n**Fischer-Tropsch type synthesis** on magnetite and other iron minerals during serpentinization produces hydrocarbons including polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) (Saladino et al., 2021, *Life* 11:31). This endogenous terrestrial source generates aromatic precursors at **200\u2013400\u00b0C** in ultramafic rock. However, selectivity for simple benzene is low; the products tend toward complex PAH mixtures.\n\n**Extraterrestrial delivery** provides perhaps the most robust prebiotic source of aromatic material. PAHs constitute **10\u201320% of interstellar carbon** (Tielens, 2008, *Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics* 46:289). The Murchison meteorite contains ~3% carbon, of which approximately **80% is incorporated into aromatic networks** (Ehrenfreund et al., 2006, *Astrobiology* 6:490). Over 60 individual PAHs have been identified in CM2 carbonaceous chondrites (Huang et al., 2015, *Earth and Planetary Science Letters* 426:101), and isotopic analysis of Ryugu samples confirms interstellar origin for naphthalene, fluoranthene, and pyrene (Aponte et al., 2023, *Science* 382:eadg6304). Meteoritic bombardment during the Late Heavy Bombardment could have seeded the early Earth with substantial aromatic inventories.\n\nOther proposed mechanisms include **Diels-Alder cycloadditions** (forming cyclohexene intermediates that aromatize via dehydrogenation), **propargyl radical self-recombination** (2 C\u2083H\u2083 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086, barrierless but requiring stabilization), and **Friedel-Crafts alkylation** in serpentinite clay nanopores (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018, *Nature* 564:59, demonstrated for tryptophan). The M\u00e9nez pathway is particularly intriguing: iron-rich saponite clay acts as a Lewis acid catalyst for electrophilic aromatic substitution at **~100\u00b0C, pH ~8.5**, within confined mineral nanopores beneath the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.\n\n---\n\n## Key intermediates define multiple convergent pathways\n\nSeveral molecular intermediates serve as branch points connecting aromatic ring chemistry to amino acid formation:\n\n- **Phenylacetaldehyde** (C\u2086H\u2085CH\u2082CHO) is the primary Strecker precursor for phenylalanine. It can be generated from phenylacetylene via H\u2082S hydration (Friedmann-Miller route) or from phenylpyruvate via non-oxidative decarboxylation. Its Strecker reaction with NH\u2083 and HCN has activation energies of **55\u201367 kJ/mol** (Hidalgo et al., 2013, *Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry* 61:10231).\n\n- **Phenylpyruvate** (C\u2086H\u2085CH\u2082COCOOH) is arguably the most important branch point. It connects to phenylalanine via transamination (potentially catalyzed by metal ions abiotically), to phenylacetaldehyde via decarboxylation, and to benzaldehyde via oxidative cleavage. In modern biology, the phenylpyruvate pathway to phenylalanine is considered more ancient than the arogenate pathway (Yoo et al., 2013, *Nature Communications* 4:2833).\n\n- **Phenylacetylene** (C\u2086H\u2085C\u2261CH) branches to both phenylalanine (via nucleophilic H\u2082S addition) and tyrosine (via radical H\u2082S addition), and has been detected in carbon-rich circumstellar envelopes.\n\n- **Benzene** itself is the ultimate branch point to all aromatic biochemistry\u2014phenylalanine, tyrosine, tryptophan, and the aromatic nucleobases in certain proposed pathways.\n\nThe biological shikimate pathway (PEP + erythrose-4-phosphate \u2192 chorismate \u2192 prephenate \u2192 phenylpyruvate \u2192 phenylalanine) is found in bacteria, archaea, fungi, and plants, suggesting deep evolutionary origins predating the last universal common ancestor. However, its seven enzymatic steps and cofactor requirements (NAD\u207a, ATP) make a purely abiotic version implausible, and no prebiotic analog has been demonstrated.\n\n---\n\n## Experimental evidence spans spark discharge, photolysis, and meteorite analysis\n\n**Miller-Urey experiments have never directly produced phenylalanine.** The original 1953 experiment identified only glycine, alanine, \u03b2-alanine, aspartic acid, and \u03b1-aminobutyric acid (Miller, 1953, *Science* 117:528). Later analyses by Ring et al. (1972, *PNAS* 69:765) confirmed 19 amino acids\u2014all aliphatic\u2014from CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O discharge. Parker et al.'s 2011 reanalysis of Miller's archived H\u2082S-containing experiment (*PNAS* 108:5526) detected 23 amino acids and 7 organosulfur compounds but **not phenylalanine**. Johnson et al.'s 2008 reanalysis of the volcanic apparatus (*Science* 322:404) similarly found no aromatic amino acids. The consistent absence of phenylalanine across all Miller-type experiments confirms that spark discharge alone cannot form the benzene ring.\n\n**UV photolysis of PAH-containing ices produces phenylalanine.** Nuevo et al. (2007, *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society* 384:605) irradiated naphthalene mixed with H\u2082O and NH\u2083 ice at **15 K** with UV/EUV photons (4\u201320 eV). The resulting organic residue contained 13 amino acids, with **phenylalanine as the most abundant aromatic amino acid** and alanine as the most abundant aliphatic one. This experiment demonstrates that PAHs in interstellar or cometary ices can serve as direct precursors to aromatic amino acids. Importantly, Nuevo et al. (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 38:37) cautioned that aromatic amino acid production from purely aliphatic ice mixtures is inefficient and possibly artefactual\u2014a pre-existing aromatic precursor appears necessary.\n\n**Meteorite and extraterrestrial detections remain inconclusive for phenylalanine.** In the Murchison meteorite, phenylalanine has been detected but is consistently classified as a probable terrestrial contaminant (Shock & Schulte, 1990, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*). Glavin et al. (2020, NASA GSFC) explicitly noted that \"tyrosine, phenylalanine, lysine, histidine, arginine\" were **absent from indigenous meteorite inventories**, using this absence to validate the non-biological origin of other amino acid signatures. Ryugu samples analyzed by Naraoka et al. (2023, *Science* 379:eabn9033) contain 13\u201323 amino acids, all aliphatic. Phenylalanine was not detected in comets 67P (Altwegg et al., 2016, *Science Advances* 2:e1600285\u2014only glycine confirmed) or Wild 2 (Elsila et al., 2009, *Meteoritics & Planetary Science* 44:1323). The pattern is stark: **aromatic amino acids are absent or contaminant-attributed across all well-studied extraterrestrial samples**, while PAH precursors are abundant.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions and mineral catalysts define a multi-setting synthesis landscape\n\nNo single early-Earth environment favors all steps of phenylalanine synthesis. The most plausible scenario involves **multiple coupled environments**:\n\n**Aromatic ring formation** is best served by high-energy settings: volcanic/hydrothermal systems where Fischer-Tropsch chemistry on magnetite generates PAHs at 200\u2013400\u00b0C; serpentinizing lithosphere where Fe-rich saponite catalyzes Friedel-Crafts reactions at ~100\u00b0C (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018); or exogenous delivery via meteoritic PAHs. Acetylene cyclotrimerization on transition metal surfaces (Fe, Ni, Cu) provides another terrestrial route, requiring metal-rich mineral environments and a source of acetylene from volcanic outgassing or discharge chemistry.\n\n**Strecker synthesis** (attaching the amino acid backbone) operates optimally in **aqueous environments at moderate temperatures (<100\u00b0C)**, requiring dissolved HCN, NH\u2083, and the appropriate aldehyde. Alkaline hydrothermal vent mixing zones, where H\u2082-rich fluids meet CO\u2082-rich seawater, create thermodynamically favorable conditions for amino acid synthesis from inorganic precursors (Kitadai, 2015, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 45:377).\n\n**Phenylalanine stability** constrains the thermal window. Below **~190\u00b0C**, phenylalanine conversion is extremely low (Chen et al., 2014, *Journal of Fuel Chemistry and Technology* 42:61). At **220\u2013280\u00b0C**, rapid decarboxylation produces phenylethylamine and subsequently styrene (Aspin et al., 2025, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 398:44). The aromatic ring itself survives even hydrothermal gasification (K\u00f6rner, 2021, *ChemSusChem* 14:4947). Critically, **extreme pH** (acidic or alkaline) and **dissolved metal salts** (Fe, Cu chlorides) inhibit decomposition, while dissolved H\u2082 also suppresses breakdown\u2014all conditions found at hydrothermal vents.\n\nThe mineral catalyst landscape relevant to phenylalanine synthesis includes:\n\n- **Iron-rich saponite**: The only mineral directly implicated in aromatic amino acid synthesis, acting as a Friedel-Crafts Lewis acid catalyst in clay nanopores (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018)\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Catalyzes reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2006) and generates D-amino acid enantiomeric excesses of **14.5\u201342.4%** via photocatalysis (2024, *Nature Communications*)\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Drives Fischer-Tropsch PAH synthesis during serpentinization; promotes glycine polymerization at 200\u00b0C and 50\u20133500 MPa (P\u00e9rez-Villa et al., 2020, *ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*)\n- **Montmorillonite**: Catalyzes polymerization (RNA oligomers up to 50-mers at 100\u20131000\u00d7 rate enhancement; Ferris, 2002, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B* 361:1777) and amino acid-sugar reactions\n- **ZnS (sphalerite)**: Photocatalyzes reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids under UV (Wang et al., 2013, *International Journal of Astrobiology* 12:69); chiral mesostructured ZnS achieves **ee >96%** from CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 (2024, *Chem*)\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase)**: Photocatalyzes formamide conversion to biomolecules at band gap **3.1 eV** (UV-activated) and enhances peptide polymerization efficiency by 23% (Leyton et al., 2012, *Amino Acids* 42:2079)\n\n---\n\n## Unresolved challenges and the path forward\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of phenylalanine faces several interconnected challenges that define the frontier of this field.\n\n**The aromatic ring problem remains unsolved in aqueous systems.** Every demonstrated route to the benzene ring\u2014cyclotrimerization, Fischer-Tropsch, pyrolysis\u2014requires either high temperatures, metal surfaces, or gas-phase conditions incompatible with the aqueous Strecker chemistry needed for the subsequent amino acid synthesis step. No one-pot aqueous synthesis from simple C\u2081 precursors to phenylalanine has been achieved. The Friedmann-Miller pathway explicitly requires separate environments for ring formation (pyrolysis) and amino acid assembly (solution phase), implying that prebiotic synthesis networks must incorporate spatial or temporal transitions between distinct geochemical settings.\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry does not reach aromatic amino acids.** The powerful Sutherland-Powner cyanosulfidic network (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301) produces precursors of glycine, alanine, serine, and threonine via HCN reductive homologation, but its C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 intermediates cannot assemble into six-membered aromatic rings. Extending cyanosulfidic protometabolism to phenylalanine remains an open theoretical challenge with no clear chemical pathway.\n\n**Chirality is an unresolved dimension.** Prebiotic Strecker synthesis produces racemic phenylalanine. While pyrite photocatalysis generates D-amino acid excesses up to 42.4%, and chiral ZnS achieves >96% ee, these mechanisms produce the wrong enantiomer (D rather than biological L) or have not been demonstrated for phenylalanine specifically. UV-circularly polarized light generates only ~0.5\u20132.5% ee. Amino acid racemization half-lives at surface temperatures are **10\u2075\u201310\u2076 years** (Bada, 1995), eroding any initial enantiomeric excess. Homochirality most likely emerged at or after the origin of life, not during prebiotic amino acid synthesis.\n\n**Phenylalanine is a \"late\" amino acid in genetic code evolution.** Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology* 9:483) classified amino acids by thermodynamic favorability and prebiotic abundance. The **10 \"early\" amino acids**\u2014glycine, alanine, aspartate, glutamate, valine, leucine, isoleucine, proline, serine, and threonine\u2014are all readily produced in Miller-Urey experiments and found in meteorites. Phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan consistently fall in the \"late\" group, correlating with the difficulty of abiotic aromatic ring formation. This classification is supported by phylogenetic, codon assignment, and thermodynamic evidence (Kirschning, 2022, *Chemistry \u2013 A European Journal* 28:e202201419).\n\n**The concentration problem compounds all others.** Even if phenylalanine or its precursors can be synthesized, dilution in a prebiotically vast ocean makes accumulation difficult. Mineral surface adsorption (pyrite, montmorillonite), evaporitic pool concentration via wet-dry cycling, porous vent chimney microreactors, clay interlayer nanopores, and ice eutectic concentration all offer partial solutions, but none has been demonstrated specifically for the phenylalanine synthesis network.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nPrebiotic phenylalanine synthesis is constrained to a narrow set of validated and proposed pathways, all requiring the prior formation of an aromatic ring\u2014the field's central unsolved problem. The **Friedmann-Miller phenylacetylene route** (1969) remains the only experimentally demonstrated end-to-end synthesis and should anchor any synthesis network design. **UV photolysis of PAH-containing ices** (Nuevo et al., 2007) provides a complementary astrophysical pathway. The most promising emerging direction is **Friedel-Crafts chemistry in iron-rich clay nanopores** (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018), which could unify aromatic ring formation and functionalization in a single mineral-hosted environment. For network design, the critical insight is that phenylalanine synthesis is inherently a **multi-environment process**: aromatic precursors must be generated in high-energy settings (volcanic, pyrolytic, or extraterrestrial), then transported to moderate aqueous environments where Strecker or transamination chemistry completes the amino acid. The mineral catalysts most relevant to bridging this gap\u2014Fe-rich saponite, pyrite, and magnetite\u2014all occur in serpentinizing systems, making alkaline hydrothermal vent complexes the most geologically coherent single setting for exploring prebiotic phenylalanine synthesis networks.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.78\n- Feedback: The network has strong topology and captures the key literature insight that phenylalanine synthesis is inherently multi-environmental. Its major strength is that it anchors the target synthesis on the experimentally validated Friedmann-Miller route and correctly identifies phenylacetaldehyde and phenylalanine aminonitrile as central hubs linking high-energy aromatic chemistry to aqueous Strecker chemistry. Network connectivity is good, hub usage is substantial, and the hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical progression is generally coherent. However, the network falls short of approval because several auxiliary branches are chemically overextended or insufficiently literature-grounded. In particular, direct hydrothermal formation of acetylene from methane/CO2/H2, direct benzene-to-phenylpyruvate conversion, the oxidative phenylpyruvate-to-benzaldehyde node under anoxic prebiotic conditions, and the compressed benzaldehyde/acetylene-to-phenylacetylene step are weak. The PAH photolysis route is literature-based but miscast as a simple surface one-step reaction rather than cryogenic UV ice photochemistry. Literature alignment is mixed: the canonical core is excellent, but several expanded branches are speculative and not supported by the provided research. A pruned network centered on the validated Friedmann-Miller sequence plus a carefully represented PAH-ice branch would score much higher.\n- Issues: ['This pathway is the weakest major branch. Direct conversion of benzene and CO2 to phenylpyruvate in a single hydrothermal mineral-hosted step is not supported by the literature and is chemically implausible as written. The transamination step from phenylpyruvate to phenylalanine is conceptually plausible, but no adequate amino donor is included and the abiotic conditions are underspecified.', 'This branch benefits from using phenylacetaldehyde as a convergent Strecker precursor, but the entry step to phenylpyruvate remains poorly supported. Decarboxylation of phenylpyruvate to phenylacetaldehyde is plausible at elevated temperature, yet the network should acknowledge that such conditions can also threaten product stability and are not directly established as a productive prebiotic route here.', 'The pathway is literature-inspired because UV photolysis of naphthalene-containing ices can yield phenylalanine. However, representing this as a single surface reaction from naphthalene plus ammonia directly to phenylalanine oversimplifies the actual ice photochemistry, which also requires water ice, UV/EUV irradiation, cryogenic conditions, and complex residue chemistry. It is plausible as a separate exogenous route but weakly integrated with the terrestrial network.', 'This is a creative network-recycling branch but not strongly grounded in the supplied literature. The phenylpyruvate-to-benzaldehyde relation is real in some oxidative contexts, yet an abiotic prebiotic oxidative cleavage node is not well justified under anoxic conditions. The benzaldehyde plus acetylene to phenylacetylene step is also highly compressed and lacks direct support.', 'This route accumulates multiple speculative steps. While the acetylene-to-benzene core is plausible, the later phenylpyruvate/benzaldehyde recycling sequence is not convincingly prebiotic as represented. Too much of the pathway depends on unsupported transformations.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Phenylalanine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network anchors phenylalanine synthesis on the only experimentally validated end-to-end prebiotic route, the Friedmann-Miller phenylacetylene pathway, and supplements it only with literature-supported convergent entries to the same key hubs. High-energy hydrothermal or pyrolytic settings generate aromatic precursors (especially phenylacetylene and benzene/PAH-related material), surface aqueous settings convert phenylacetaldehyde into the Strecker aminonitrile and then phenylalanine, and biochemical/prebiotic settings provide limited downstream or alternative conversion through phenylpyruvate transamination and concentration/polymer-association. The design avoids unsupported direct benzene-to-phenylpyruvate or oxidative cleavage steps, explicitly represents the PAH-ice photolysis result as a separate cryogenic exogenous branch feeding the same target, and uses phenylacetaldehyde, phenylalanine aminonitrile, phenylpyruvate, ammonia, and hydrogen cyanide as the main hubs linking hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"benzene\",\n      \"common_name\": \"benzene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H6/c1-2-4-6-5-3-1/h1-6H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"C8H6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethynylbenzene\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylacetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C8H6/c1-2-8-6-4-3-5-7-8/h1,3-7H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C8H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C8H8O/c9-6-7-8-4-2-1-3-5-8/h1-6H,7H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-phenylpropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylalanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C9H10N2/c10-7-9(11)6-8-4-2-1-3-5-8/h1-5,9H,6,11H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-phenylpropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylalanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C9H11NO2/c10-8(9(11)12)6-7-4-2-1-3-5-7/h1-5,8H,6,10H2,(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxo-3-phenylpropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phenylpyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C9H8O3/c10-8(9(11)12)6-7-4-2-1-3-5-7/h1-5H,6H2,(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H8\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"naphthalene\",\n      \"common_name\": \"naphthalene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C10H8/c1-2-6-10-8-4-3-7-9(10)5-1/h1-8H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of acetylene from reduced carbon feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"473-673K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization-associated reducing conditions; hydrothermal gas/mineral interfaces; product distribution broad and acetylene yield likely low\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced carbon species formed in Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal chemistry include small unsaturated hydrocarbons that can supply acetylene to downstream aromatic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a conservative connector step justified by hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite/iron minerals producing hydrocarbons and aromatic precursors in serpentinizing systems, though not selectively optimized for acetylene. It is included because Friedmann and Miller used methane/acetylene-class feedstocks as entry points to phenylacetylene, and endogenous hydrothermal production of reduced hydrocarbons is supported in serpentinization settings (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Saladino et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Transition-metal-catalyzed acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"transition-metal-bearing mineral surfaces represented by magnetite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"metal-rich vent-wall or gas/mineral interface; kinetically difficult without catalysis; literature establishes catalytic feasibility on transition-metal surfaces but not exact prebiotic selectivity on these specific minerals\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three acetylene molecules undergo surface-assisted cyclotrimerization through metallacyclic intermediates to produce benzene.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerization is a literature-supported solution to the aromatic ring problem, with strong catalytic acceleration on metal surfaces and transition-metal systems. The exact best-studied catalysts are Ag(111), zinc acetate, and Fe+-ice clusters rather than vent minerals, so this hydrothermal mineral-hosted representation is somewhat generalized but remains grounded in the literature that Fe/Ni/Cu-type surfaces can mediate the chemistry. The step is used only as a convergent aromatic-entry branch and not as a direct route to phenylalanine without the validated downstream Friedmann-Miller sequence (Wang et al., 2019; Shuman et al., 2022; Cinar et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"High-energy formation of phenylacetylene from methane/acetylene/benzene feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-650K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"pyrolytic/electric-discharge/UV-assisted high-energy regime at volcanic-hydrothermal interfaces; substantial phenylacetylene reported from methane, acetylene, or benzene under high-energy conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy gas-phase and mineral-surface reactions convert reduced hydrocarbon mixtures and aromatic precursors into phenylacetylene.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key aromatic-precursor step from the experimentally validated Friedmann-Miller route. Friedmann and Miller specifically reported phenylacetylene generation from methane, acetylene, or benzene via pyrolysis, electric discharge, or UV irradiation. The mineral agents here represent plausible hydrothermal/volcanic mineral surfaces required by the schema, but the core evidence is the high-energy prebiotic synthesis itself, not selective mineral catalysis. This step should be treated as the main bottleneck in terrestrial phenylalanine synthesis (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"H2S-mediated hydration of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration on montmorillonite with UV-accessible TiO2-rich surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aqueous sulfide-bearing solution; thioaldehyde intermediate implied then hydrolyzed; moderate-temperature transfer from high-energy aromatic source into solution chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic and radical addition of H2S across the alkyne generates sulfur-bearing intermediates that hydrolyze to phenylacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the distinctive second step of the validated Friedmann-Miller sequence. The literature supports H2S-mediated conversion of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde through sulfur addition and hydrolysis. Surface minerals here serve concentration and interface roles required by the network schema rather than being the primary experimentally demonstrated catalyst. This moderate aqueous step is exactly the environmental shift emphasized by Miller's later review (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Aqueous Strecker synthesis of phenylalanine aminonitrile from phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"moderate-temperature aqueous Strecker conditions; concentration in pools or evaporitic margins; activation energy reported for related Strecker chemistry 55-67 kJ/mol\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phenylacetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give the alpha-aminonitrile precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Phenylacetaldehyde is the primary Strecker precursor identified in the literature for phenylalanine. Friedmann and Miller completed this conversion experimentally, and Strecker addition to aldehydes is a standard prebiotic route under aqueous conditions. Mineral agents here plausibly aid concentration and adsorption, but the central support is the classical Strecker mechanism applied to phenylacetaldehyde (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Hidalgo et al., 2013; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of phenylalanine aminonitrile to phenylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite), montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis in concentrated pools or geothermal margins; racemic product expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final transformation completes the validated Friedmann-Miller route to phenylalanine. Aminonitrile hydrolysis under prebiotic aqueous conditions is consistent with classical Strecker chemistry. The literature specifically identifies this overall sequence as the only experimentally validated end-to-end phenylalanine synthesis under plausible prebiotic conditions (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cryogenic UV photolysis of PAH-containing ice to phenylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"15K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none demonstrated; listed agents represent possible later surface adsorption/concentration upon delivery\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene + H2O + NH3 ice; exogenous or icy microenvironment branch; complex residue chemistry rather than one-pot aqueous synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV/EUV processing of PAH-containing ice generates complex photoproduct residues that include aromatic amino acids, among them phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This branch is included exactly as a separate cryogenic PAH-ice photochemistry route, correcting prior oversimplification. Nuevo and coworkers showed that UV photolysis of naphthalene-containing H2O/NH3 ices at 15 K yields phenylalanine in the residue. This route bypasses the terrestrial phenylacetaldehyde/Strecker hub but is still literature-supported as a complementary source of phenylalanine or aromatic precursors delivered to the early Earth. The mineral agents are not mechanistic catalysts in the original experiment and are included only to satisfy schema constraints for surface nodes; the reasoning explicitly preserves the true cryogenic photochemical context (Nuevo et al., 2007; Nuevo et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Non-oxidative decarboxylation of phenylpyruvate to phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"thermal decarboxylation analog; used as a connecting prebiotic branch to the validated Strecker precursor; elevated temperature can compete with decomposition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of the alpha-keto acid shortens the side chain carbonyl system to the corresponding aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies phenylpyruvate as a major branch point connected to phenylacetaldehyde by non-oxidative decarboxylation, making this a justified connector into the validated Strecker sequence. This reaction is less directly demonstrated prebiotically than the Friedmann-Miller core and should therefore be regarded as a literature-guided but less experimentally anchored auxiliary branch. It is included because the report specifically highlights phenylpyruvate-to-phenylacetaldehyde connectivity, while warning that temperature control is important for product stability (Yoo et al., 2013; Aspin et al., 2025; Chen et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Abiotic transamination/reductive amination of phenylpyruvate to phenylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved metal ions plausible but unspecified\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool or mineral-interface setting; abiotic metal-ion-assisted transamination/reductive amination proposed, not end-to-end validated for phenylalanine in the supplied literature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-keto acid accepts nitrogen through abiotic transamination or reductive amination to yield the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report explicitly identifies phenylpyruvate as perhaps the most important branch point and states that it connects to phenylalanine via transamination, potentially catalyzed abiotically by metal ions. Because a specific prebiotic phenylpyruvate synthesis route was not established in the provided literature, this reaction is retained only as a downstream connector for any phenylpyruvate generated in broader protometabolic networks. It is therefore more speculative than the Friedmann-Miller core but still literature-guided rather than invented (Yoo et al., 2013; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Wang et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal generation of aromatic feedstocks by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"473-673K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization and ultramafic rock-water interaction; low selectivity with PAH-rich product mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type mineral catalysis in reducing hydrothermal settings generates mixtures of hydrocarbons and aromatic species including benzene-class compounds and PAH precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature supports endogenous hydrothermal production of aromatic hydrocarbons and PAHs during serpentinization and Fischer-Tropsch-type processes on iron minerals, though selectivity for simple benzene is limited. This reaction creates the geochemical bridge between hydrothermal carbon fixation chemistry and the aromatic inventory needed for later phenylacetylene or PAH-ice routes without asserting unsupported direct conversion to phenylalanine intermediates (Saladino et al., 2021; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"High-energy aromatic elaboration from benzene to phenylacetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-650K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"volcanic or pyrolytic interface with electric-discharge/UV input; represents benzene/acetylene entry specifically noted by Friedmann and Miller\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic aromatic hydrocarbon chemistry couples benzene-class precursors with acetylene-derived unsaturation to produce phenylacetylene.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann and Miller explicitly identified benzene and acetylene among feedstocks that generate phenylacetylene under pyrolysis, discharge, or UV conditions. This reaction isolates that specific entry rather than forcing all feeds into one compressed step, improving literature fidelity and avoiding unsupported downstream shortcuts. It remains a high-energy prebiotic conversion rather than a mild aqueous process (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller methane branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Methane enters high-energy aromatic chemistry, forming phenylacetylene, then H2S hydration and Strecker chemistry yield phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller acetylene branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetylene serves as the direct high-energy precursor to phenylacetylene, followed by the validated aqueous steps to phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller benzene branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Benzene enters the phenylacetylene-forming high-energy regime, then converges onto phenylacetaldehyde and Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyclotrimerization-to-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerizes to benzene on catalytic mineral/metal surfaces, then proceeds through phenylacetylene and the validated aqueous sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aromatic inventory route via Fischer-Tropsch products\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch chemistry generates benzene/PAH feedstocks; the benzene fraction enters phenylacetylene chemistry and then the validated Strecker sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal methane-to-benzene convergent route\",\n      \"description\": \"Methane-derived reduced carbon produces acetylene, which cyclotrimerizes to benzene before entering the phenylacetylene branch and aqueous Strecker steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylpyruvate decarboxylation entry to validated Strecker hub\",\n      \"description\": \"Phenylpyruvate thermally decarboxylates to phenylacetaldehyde, which then undergoes Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylpyruvate direct transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Phenylpyruvate is converted directly to phenylalanine by abiotic transamination/reductive amination in prebiotic pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Cryogenic PAH-ice photochemical route\",\n      \"description\": \"Naphthalene-containing H2O/NH3 ice under UV/EUV irradiation yields phenylalanine directly in organic residue, representing an exogenous or icy branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"PAH inventory to direct icy phenylalanine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch aromatic production supplies PAH-like feedstocks that, upon transfer to icy photochemical settings, can contribute to phenylalanine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Phenylalanine", "overall_strategy": "This network anchors phenylalanine synthesis on the only experimentally validated end-to-end prebiotic route, the Friedmann-Miller phenylacetylene pathway, and supplements it only with literature-supported convergent entries to the same key hubs. High-energy hydrothermal or pyrolytic settings generate aromatic precursors (especially phenylacetylene and benzene/PAH-related material), surface aqueous settings convert phenylacetaldehyde into the Strecker aminonitrile and then phenylalanine, and biochemical/prebiotic settings provide limited downstream or alternative conversion through phenylpyruvate transamination and concentration/polymer-association. The design avoids unsupported direct benzene-to-phenylpyruvate or oxidative cleavage steps, explicitly represents the PAH-ice photolysis result as a separate cryogenic exogenous branch feeding the same target, and uses phenylacetaldehyde, phenylalanine aminonitrile, phenylpyruvate, ammonia, and hydrogen cyanide as the main hubs linking hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "C6H6", "iupac_name": "benzene", "common_name": "benzene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6/c1-2-4-6-5-3-1/h1-6H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "C8H6", "iupac_name": "ethynylbenzene", "common_name": "phenylacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C8H6/c1-2-8-6-4-3-5-7-8/h1,3-7H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C8H8O", "iupac_name": "2-phenylacetaldehyde", "common_name": "phenylacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C8H8O/c9-6-7-8-4-2-1-3-5-8/h1-6H,7H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C9H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-phenylpropanenitrile", "common_name": "phenylalanine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C9H10N2/c10-7-9(11)6-8-4-2-1-3-5-8/h1-5,9H,6,11H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C9H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-phenylpropanoic acid", "common_name": "phenylalanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C9H11NO2/c10-8(9(11)12)6-7-4-2-1-3-5-7/h1-5,8H,6,10H2,(H,11,12)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C9H8O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-phenylpropanoic acid", "common_name": "phenylpyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C9H8O3/c10-8(9(11)12)6-7-4-2-1-3-5-7/h1-5H,6H2,(H,11,12)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C10H8", "iupac_name": "naphthalene", "common_name": "naphthalene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H8/c1-2-6-10-8-4-3-7-9(10)5-1/h1-8H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of acetylene from reduced carbon feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "473-673K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": true, "other": "serpentinization-associated reducing conditions; hydrothermal gas/mineral interfaces; product distribution broad and acetylene yield likely low"}, "mechanism": "Reduced carbon species formed in Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal chemistry include small unsaturated hydrocarbons that can supply acetylene to downstream aromatic chemistry.", "reasoning": "This is a conservative connector step justified by hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite/iron minerals producing hydrocarbons and aromatic precursors in serpentinizing systems, though not selectively optimized for acetylene. It is included because Friedmann and Miller used methane/acetylene-class feedstocks as entry points to phenylacetylene, and endogenous hydrothermal production of reduced hydrocarbons is supported in serpentinization settings (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Saladino et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Transition-metal-catalyzed acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene", "inputs": ["mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "transition-metal-bearing mineral surfaces represented by magnetite and pyrite", "aqueous": false, "other": "metal-rich vent-wall or gas/mineral interface; kinetically difficult without catalysis; literature establishes catalytic feasibility on transition-metal surfaces but not exact prebiotic selectivity on these specific minerals"}, "mechanism": "Three acetylene molecules undergo surface-assisted cyclotrimerization through metallacyclic intermediates to produce benzene.", "reasoning": "Acetylene cyclotrimerization is a literature-supported solution to the aromatic ring problem, with strong catalytic acceleration on metal surfaces and transition-metal systems. The exact best-studied catalysts are Ag(111), zinc acetate, and Fe+-ice clusters rather than vent minerals, so this hydrothermal mineral-hosted representation is somewhat generalized but remains grounded in the literature that Fe/Ni/Cu-type surfaces can mediate the chemistry. The step is used only as a convergent aromatic-entry branch and not as a direct route to phenylalanine without the validated downstream Friedmann-Miller sequence (Wang et al., 2019; Shuman et al., 2022; Cinar et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "High-energy formation of phenylacetylene from methane/acetylene/benzene feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-650K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), pyrite (FeS2)", "aqueous": false, "other": "pyrolytic/electric-discharge/UV-assisted high-energy regime at volcanic-hydrothermal interfaces; substantial phenylacetylene reported from methane, acetylene, or benzene under high-energy conditions"}, "mechanism": "High-energy gas-phase and mineral-surface reactions convert reduced hydrocarbon mixtures and aromatic precursors into phenylacetylene.", "reasoning": "This is the key aromatic-precursor step from the experimentally validated Friedmann-Miller route. Friedmann and Miller specifically reported phenylacetylene generation from methane, acetylene, or benzene via pyrolysis, electric discharge, or UV irradiation. The mineral agents here represent plausible hydrothermal/volcanic mineral surfaces required by the schema, but the core evidence is the high-energy prebiotic synthesis itself, not selective mineral catalysis. This step should be treated as the main bottleneck in terrestrial phenylalanine synthesis (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "H2S-mediated hydration of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration on montmorillonite with UV-accessible TiO2-rich surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "aqueous sulfide-bearing solution; thioaldehyde intermediate implied then hydrolyzed; moderate-temperature transfer from high-energy aromatic source into solution chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic and radical addition of H2S across the alkyne generates sulfur-bearing intermediates that hydrolyze to phenylacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the distinctive second step of the validated Friedmann-Miller sequence. The literature supports H2S-mediated conversion of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde through sulfur addition and hydrolysis. Surface minerals here serve concentration and interface roles required by the network schema rather than being the primary experimentally demonstrated catalyst. This moderate aqueous step is exactly the environmental shift emphasized by Miller's later review (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Aqueous Strecker synthesis of phenylalanine aminonitrile from phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "aqueous": true, "other": "moderate-temperature aqueous Strecker conditions; concentration in pools or evaporitic margins; activation energy reported for related Strecker chemistry 55-67 kJ/mol"}, "mechanism": "Phenylacetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give the alpha-aminonitrile precursor.", "reasoning": "Phenylacetaldehyde is the primary Strecker precursor identified in the literature for phenylalanine. Friedmann and Miller completed this conversion experimentally, and Strecker addition to aldehydes is a standard prebiotic route under aqueous conditions. Mineral agents here plausibly aid concentration and adsorption, but the central support is the classical Strecker mechanism applied to phenylacetaldehyde (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Hidalgo et al., 2013; Miller, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrolysis of phenylalanine aminonitrile to phenylalanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite), montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "aqueous hydrolysis in concentrated pools or geothermal margins; racemic product expected"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "This final transformation completes the validated Friedmann-Miller route to phenylalanine. Aminonitrile hydrolysis under prebiotic aqueous conditions is consistent with classical Strecker chemistry. The literature specifically identifies this overall sequence as the only experimentally validated end-to-end phenylalanine synthesis under plausible prebiotic conditions (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cryogenic UV photolysis of PAH-containing ice to phenylalanine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_007", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "15K", "pressure": "low", "catalyst": "none demonstrated; listed agents represent possible later surface adsorption/concentration upon delivery", "aqueous": false, "other": "UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene + H2O + NH3 ice; exogenous or icy microenvironment branch; complex residue chemistry rather than one-pot aqueous synthesis"}, "mechanism": "UV/EUV processing of PAH-containing ice generates complex photoproduct residues that include aromatic amino acids, among them phenylalanine.", "reasoning": "This branch is included exactly as a separate cryogenic PAH-ice photochemistry route, correcting prior oversimplification. Nuevo and coworkers showed that UV photolysis of naphthalene-containing H2O/NH3 ices at 15 K yields phenylalanine in the residue. This route bypasses the terrestrial phenylacetaldehyde/Strecker hub but is still literature-supported as a complementary source of phenylalanine or aromatic precursors delivered to the early Earth. The mineral agents are not mechanistic catalysts in the original experiment and are included only to satisfy schema constraints for surface nodes; the reasoning explicitly preserves the true cryogenic photochemical context (Nuevo et al., 2007; Nuevo et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Non-oxidative decarboxylation of phenylpyruvate to phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "thermal decarboxylation analog; used as a connecting prebiotic branch to the validated Strecker precursor; elevated temperature can compete with decomposition"}, "mechanism": "Thermal decarboxylation of the alpha-keto acid shortens the side chain carbonyl system to the corresponding aldehyde.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies phenylpyruvate as a major branch point connected to phenylacetaldehyde by non-oxidative decarboxylation, making this a justified connector into the validated Strecker sequence. This reaction is less directly demonstrated prebiotically than the Friedmann-Miller core and should therefore be regarded as a literature-guided but less experimentally anchored auxiliary branch. It is included because the report specifically highlights phenylpyruvate-to-phenylacetaldehyde connectivity, while warning that temperature control is important for product stability (Yoo et al., 2013; Aspin et al., 2025; Chen et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Abiotic transamination/reductive amination of phenylpyruvate to phenylalanine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "dissolved metal ions plausible but unspecified", "aqueous": true, "other": "prebiotic pool or mineral-interface setting; abiotic metal-ion-assisted transamination/reductive amination proposed, not end-to-end validated for phenylalanine in the supplied literature"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-keto acid accepts nitrogen through abiotic transamination or reductive amination to yield the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "The deep research report explicitly identifies phenylpyruvate as perhaps the most important branch point and states that it connects to phenylalanine via transamination, potentially catalyzed abiotically by metal ions. Because a specific prebiotic phenylpyruvate synthesis route was not established in the provided literature, this reaction is retained only as a downstream connector for any phenylpyruvate generated in broader protometabolic networks. It is therefore more speculative than the Friedmann-Miller core but still literature-guided rather than invented (Yoo et al., 2013; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Wang et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of aromatic feedstocks by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "473-673K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": true, "other": "serpentinization and ultramafic rock-water interaction; low selectivity with PAH-rich product mixtures"}, "mechanism": "Fischer-Tropsch-type mineral catalysis in reducing hydrothermal settings generates mixtures of hydrocarbons and aromatic species including benzene-class compounds and PAH precursors.", "reasoning": "The literature supports endogenous hydrothermal production of aromatic hydrocarbons and PAHs during serpentinization and Fischer-Tropsch-type processes on iron minerals, though selectivity for simple benzene is limited. This reaction creates the geochemical bridge between hydrothermal carbon fixation chemistry and the aromatic inventory needed for later phenylacetylene or PAH-ice routes without asserting unsupported direct conversion to phenylalanine intermediates (Saladino et al., 2021; Miller, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "High-energy aromatic elaboration from benzene to phenylacetylene", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-650K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": false, "other": "volcanic or pyrolytic interface with electric-discharge/UV input; represents benzene/acetylene entry specifically noted by Friedmann and Miller"}, "mechanism": "Energetic aromatic hydrocarbon chemistry couples benzene-class precursors with acetylene-derived unsaturation to produce phenylacetylene.", "reasoning": "Friedmann and Miller explicitly identified benzene and acetylene among feedstocks that generate phenylacetylene under pyrolysis, discharge, or UV conditions. This reaction isolates that specific entry rather than forcing all feeds into one compressed step, improving literature fidelity and avoiding unsupported downstream shortcuts. It remains a high-energy prebiotic conversion rather than a mild aqueous process (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Friedmann-Miller methane branch", "description": "Methane enters high-energy aromatic chemistry, forming phenylacetylene, then H2S hydration and Strecker chemistry yield phenylalanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Canonical Friedmann-Miller acetylene branch", "description": "Acetylene serves as the direct high-energy precursor to phenylacetylene, followed by the validated aqueous steps to phenylalanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Canonical Friedmann-Miller benzene branch", "description": "Benzene enters the phenylacetylene-forming high-energy regime, then converges onto phenylacetaldehyde and Strecker synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Cyclotrimerization-to-Strecker route", "description": "Acetylene cyclotrimerizes to benzene on catalytic mineral/metal surfaces, then proceeds through phenylacetylene and the validated aqueous sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal aromatic inventory route via Fischer-Tropsch products", "description": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch chemistry generates benzene/PAH feedstocks; the benzene fraction enters phenylacetylene chemistry and then the validated Strecker sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal methane-to-benzene convergent route", "description": "Methane-derived reduced carbon produces acetylene, which cyclotrimerizes to benzene before entering the phenylacetylene branch and aqueous Strecker steps.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Phenylpyruvate decarboxylation entry to validated Strecker hub", "description": "Phenylpyruvate thermally decarboxylates to phenylacetaldehyde, which then undergoes Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to phenylalanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_00