e and reflects the aromatic ring bottleneck discussed in the literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use pyrolysis/discharge to generate acetylene, then metal-catalyzed cyclotrimerization to benzene\",\n        \"Specify relevant catalytic surfaces such as Fe/Ni/Cu rather than leaving the hydrothermal entry generic\",\n        \"Distinguish clearly between hydrothermal mineral catalysis and gas-phase high-energy chemistry\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.94\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route leverages Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal production of aromatic inventory, which is broadly supported for PAHs and hydrocarbons on magnetite during serpentinization. It is plausible as an inventory-building branch, but less validated for selective benzene or naphthalene production than the network presentation may imply. Once benzene is available, the route reconnects to the stronger Friedmann-Miller chemistry.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Frame rxn_010 as low-selectivity aromatic inventory generation rather than efficient direct benzene/naphthalene synthesis\",\n        \"Include specific minerals such as magnetite and note 200-400C serpentinization conditions\",\n        \"Acknowledge that this branch is supportive inventory chemistry, not an experimentally validated end-to-end phenylalanine path\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n