le mild aqueous pathway. Magnetite-bearing hydrothermal systems are a geologically coherent source of hydrocarbon precursors, though direct selective acetylene formation remains less constrained than later steps and is included here as a necessary high-energy entry consistent with the reported pyrolytic chemistry (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974; Saladino et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene on iron-rich mineral surfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"transition-metal-rich mineral surface catalysis; acetylene-rich microenvironments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three acetylene molecules cyclotrimerize via surface-stabilized organometallic-like intermediates to benzene.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetylene cyclotrimerization is thermodynamically favorable but kinetically blocked without catalysis. Modern studies show metal surfaces strongly lower barriers and can produce benzene with high selectivity; Fe-bearing prebiotic mineral surfaces are therefore a plausible terrestrial analog. The network uses iron-rich mineral surfaces to represent transition-metal-assisted cyclotrimerization while remaining within the allowed hydrothermal mineral set. This addresses the aromatic ring bottleneck without invoking unsupported aqueous benzene formation (Wang et al., 2019; Cinar et al., 2024; Shuman et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type aromatic generation producing PAHs\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"473-673K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization-associated Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis in ultramafic systems; aromatic selectivity low\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction and oligomerization of simple carbon feedstocks on iron minerals yields hydrocarbons and aromatic mixtures including PAHs such as naphthalene.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on magnetite and related iron minerals in serpentinizing systems produces hydrocarbons and PAHs at roughly 200-400 degrees C. Selectivity for benzene is poor, but aromatic inventories are nevertheless generated. This reaction is included as a literature-grounded source of exogenous/endogenous aromatic scaffolds feeding later high-energy or photochemical steps (Saladino et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylacetylene formation from acetylene-derived aromatic precursors under high energy\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K plus episodic high-energy irradiation\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation or electric discharge at subaerial volcanic settings; condensation route summarized to reflect Friedmann-Miller precursor chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy processing of acetylene- and benzene-containing mixtures yields phenylacetylene as a kinetically accessible aryl-acetylene product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann and Miller experimentally reported substantial yields of phenylacetylene from hydrocarbons such as methane, acetylene, or benzene under pyrolysis, discharge, or UV irradiation. The exact precursor manifold is high-energy and mixture-dependent, so this network represents phenylacetylene generation from previously formed acetylene and benzene pools in a volcanic surface setting. TiO2 is included as the required mineral photocatalyst support for surface high-energy chemistry, though the key literature support is the original phenylacetylene production under pyrolytic/discharge conditions (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"H2S-mediated hydration of phenylacetylene to phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous solution; H2S addition produces sulfur-bearing intermediate that hydrolyzes to aldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic and radical H2S addition across the alkyne forms sulfur-containing intermediates or thioaldehydes that hydrolyze to phenylacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the distinctive middle step of the validated Friedmann-Miller pathway. Phenylacetylene reacts with H2S to give intermediates that hydrolyze to phenylacetaldehyde, linking aromatic ring chemistry to Strecker-compatible aldehyde chemistry. The step is specifically literature-supported and should remain central in any phenylalanine network (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of phenylalanine aminonitrile from phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aqueous anoxic Strecker conditions in concentrated evaporitic or pool settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia forms an imine/iminium with the aldehyde; cyanide attack yields the alpha-aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Phenylacetaldehyde is the principal Strecker precursor for phenylalanine. Reaction with NH3 and HCN gives the corresponding aminonitrile, the immediate precursor to phenylalanine. The Strecker step is explicitly part of the Friedmann-Miller end-to-end synthesis, and kinetic data for Strecker reactions of phenylacetaldehyde support its moderate-temperature aqueous plausibility (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Hidalgo et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of phenylalanine aminonitrile to phenylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis during prolonged pool residence or geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive nitrile hydration and hydrolysis yield the amino acid carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of the Strecker aminonitrile completes the validated Friedmann-Miller phenylalanine synthesis. This transformation is standard chemistry following aminonitrile formation and provides the direct biochemical-entry target pool (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis of PAH-containing H2O/NH3 ices yielding phenylalanine-rich residue\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"15K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene:H2O:NH3 ice; exogenous cryogenic photochemistry followed by delivery\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical functionalization and fragmentation of PAH-containing ice generates complex organic residues including amino acids, with phenylalanine among the aromatic products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nuevo and co-workers showed that UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene in H2O/NH3 ice at 15 K yields amino acids including phenylalanine, the most abundant aromatic amino acid detected in the residue. This is not a terrestrial surface aqueous route; it is represented as an exogenous branch feeding the broader prebiotic inventory, correcting earlier misclassification issues (Nuevo et al., 2007; Nuevo et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyrite-mediated reductive amination/transamination of phenylpyruvate to phenylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"metal-ion-assisted abiotic amination; included as a literature-inspired branch-point completion rather than a validated phenylalanine route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Abiotic amination of the alpha-keto acid yields the corresponding amino acid through imine formation and reduction/transamination-like chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Phenylpyruvate is identified in the literature as a major branch point connecting to phenylalanine via transamination in biology and plausibly by abiotic metal-assisted amination more generally. Direct prebiotic conversion has not been experimentally demonstrated specifically for phenylalanine, so this branch is included cautiously as a speculative but metabolically relevant connector, grounded in broader keto-acid amination chemistry and the ancient importance of the phenylpyruvate route (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Yoo et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of phenylpyruvate to phenylacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"non-oxidative thermal decarboxylation in geothermal settings; product stability window limited\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation yields the corresponding aldehyde, linking keto-acid and Strecker branches.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report identifies phenylpyruvate-to-phenylacetaldehyde conversion via non-oxidative decarboxylation as a plausible connection point. This reaction is not the validated core route but is a reasonable auxiliary convergence step if moderate heating is available. The network keeps it separate from unsupported oxidative cleavage chemistry and acknowledges thermal constraints on phenylalanine-related compounds (Yoo et al., 2013; Chen et al., 2014; Aspin et al., 2025).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of phenylalanine to styrene-forming decomposition branch\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"493-553K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"rapid decomposition window above phenylalanine stability range\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phenylalanine decarboxylates and deaminates through phenethylamine-related intermediates to styrene under elevated temperature.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is included as a sink and constraint node to encode the literature requirement that phenylalanine is thermally fragile above about 220-280 degrees C, where decarboxylation and downstream styrene formation accelerate. Including this branch helps define the environmental window for successful accumulation rather than productive synthesis (Chen et al., 2014; Aspin et al., 2025; Korner, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aromatic functionalization branch to phenylpyruvate in iron-rich clay nanopores\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"confined clay nanopore, mildly alkaline pH ~8.5; speculative network-connecting analog inspired by iron-rich saponite Friedel-Crafts chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Clay-confined aromatic functionalization and carbonyl/carboxyl incorporation generate an alpha-keto-acid aromatic product pool represented here by phenylpyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature highlights iron-rich saponite nanopore Friedel-Crafts chemistry as an emerging mineral-hosted route relevant to aromatic amino acid precursors, but it does not demonstrate direct abiotic phenylpyruvate synthesis from benzene. This step is therefore explicitly speculative and included only to connect the literature-emphasized phenylpyruvate branch into the network without invoking unsupported oxidative cleavage. The temperature and pH are taken from the clay nanopore setting described by M\u00e9nez et al. and are presented as a constrained analog rather than an established result (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018; Yoo et al., 2013).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Friedmann-Miller from methane\",\n      \"description\": \"Methane enters a high-energy hydrothermal/volcanic route to acetylene, then to benzene and phenylacetylene, followed by H2S hydration, Strecker synthesis, and aminonitrile hydrolysis to phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetylene-first Friedmann-Miller route\",\n      \"description\": \"Beginning from the acetylene hub, cyclotrimerization yields benzene, which feeds high-energy phenylacetylene formation and then the validated aqueous sequence to phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Benzene-first Friedmann-Miller route\",\n      \"description\": \"Preformed benzene from catalytic acetylene trimerization is diverted into phenylacetylene formation and then into the H2S-hydration/Strecker sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct phenylacetylene entry route\",\n      \"description\": \"If phenylacetylene is generated in a high-energy environment, the remaining validated steps are H2S hydration to phenylacetaldehyde, Strecker synthesis, and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylacetaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Phenylacetaldehyde acts as the principal convergent aldehyde precursor and undergoes Strecker synthesis followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylalanine aminonitrile hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Once the aminonitrile pool is formed, simple aqueous hydrolysis yields phenylalanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Exogenous PAH-ice photolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Naphthalene in NH3/H2O ice undergoes UV/EUV photochemistry at cryogenic temperature to produce phenylalanine directly in the organic residue, later delivered to terrestrial prebiotic settings.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal PAH generation plus exogenous-style photochemical completion\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch chemistry generates naphthalene/PAH inventory, which then participates in cryogenic UV photochemistry yielding phenylalanine upon delivery.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylpyruvate decarboxylation into the Strecker branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A speculative clay-confined aromatic functionalization branch produces phenylpyruvate, which decarboxylates to phenylacetaldehyde and then enters the validated Strecker sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Phenylpyruvate amination branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Phenylpyruvate formed in mineral-confined settings is converted directly to phenylalanine by abiotic reductive amination/transamination-like chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molec