 "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "High-energy generation of acetylene from methane-rich feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-650K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": false, "other": "pyrolytic/discharge-like high-energy vent-associated setting; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "High-energy pyrolysis/discharge fragments methane-rich feedstocks to C2 hydrocarbons including acetylene; iron-bearing mineral surfaces are included as plausible vent-associated supports rather than as the sole energetic driver.", "reasoning": "Friedmann and Miller identified methane and acetylene as plausible starting materials for phenylacetylene production under pyrolysis, electric discharge, or UV irradiation. Miller later emphasized that phenylalanine synthesis requires pyrolysis reactions coupled to solution chemistry rather than a single mild aqueous pathway. Magnetite-bearing hydrothermal systems are a geologically coherent source of hydrocarbon precursors, though direct selective acetylene formation remains less constrained than later steps and is included here as a necessary high-energy entry consistent with the reported pyrolytic chemistry (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974; Saladino et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Acetylene cyclotrimerization to benzene on iron-rich mineral surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), pyrite (FeS2)", "aqueous": 