across the alkyne forms sulfur-containing intermediates or thioaldehydes that hydrolyze to phenylacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the distinctive middle step of the validated Friedmann-Miller pathway. Phenylacetylene reacts with H2S to give intermediates that hydrolyze to phenylacetaldehyde, linking aromatic ring chemistry to Strecker-compatible aldehyde chemistry. The step is specifically literature-supported and should remain central in any phenylalanine network (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Strecker synthesis of phenylalanine aminonitrile from phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": true, "other": "aqueous anoxic Strecker conditions in concentrated evaporitic or pool settings"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia forms an imine/iminium with the aldehyde; cyanide attack yields the alpha-aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Phenylacetaldehyde is the principal Strecker precursor for phenylalanine. Reaction with NH3 and HCN gives the corresponding aminonitrile, the immediate precursor to phenylalanine. The Strecker step is explicitly part of the Friedmann-Miller end-to-end synthesis, and kinetic data for Strecker reactions of phenylacetaldehyde support its moderate-temperature aqueous plausibility (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Hidalgo et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrolysis of phenylalanine aminonitrile to phenylalanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "aqueous hydrolysis during prolonged pool residence or geothermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Successive nitrile hydration and hydrolysis yield the amino acid carboxylate.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of the Strecker aminonitrile completes the validated Friedmann-Miller phenylalanine synthesis. This transformation is standard chemistry following aminonitrile formation and provides the direct biochemical-entry target pool (Friedmann & Miller, 1969; Miller, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "UV photolysis of PAH-containing H2O/NH3 ices yielding phenylalanine-rich residue", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "15K", "pressure": "low", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": false, "other": "UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene:H2O:NH3 ice; exogenous cryogenic photochemistry followed by delivery"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical functionalization and fragmentation of PAH-containing ice generates complex organic residues including amino acids, with phenylalanine among the aromatic products.", "reasoning": "Nuevo and co-workers showed that UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene in H2O/NH3 ice at 15 K yields amino acids including phenylalanine, the most abundant aromatic amino acid detected in the residue. This is not a terrestrial surface aqueous route; it is represented as an exogenous branch feeding the broader prebiotic inventory, correcting earlier misclassification issues (Nuevo et al., 2007; Nuevo et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Pyrite-mediated reductive amination/transamination of phenylpyruvate to phenylalanine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "metal-ion-assisted abiotic amination; included as a literature-inspired branch-point completion rather than a validated phenylalanine route"}, "mechanism": "Abiotic amination of the alpha-keto acid yields the corresponding amino acid through imine formation and reduction/transamination-like chemistry.", "reasoning": "Phenylpyruvate is identified in the literature as a major branch point connecting to phenylalanine via transamination in biology and plausibly by abiotic metal-assisted amination more generally. Direct prebiotic conversion has not been experimentally demonstrated specifically for phenylalanine, so this branch is included cautiously as a speculative but metabolically relevant connector, grounded in broader keto-acid amination chemistry and the ancient importance of the phenylpyruvate route (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Yoo et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of phenylpyruvate to phenylacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "non-oxidative thermal decarboxylation in geothermal settings; product stability window limited"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation yields the corresponding aldehyde, linking keto-acid and Strecker branches.", "reasoning": "The research report identifies phenylpyruvate-to-phenylacetaldehyde conversion via non-oxidative decarboxylation as a plausible connection point. This reaction is not the validated core route but is a reasonable auxiliary convergence step if moderate heating is available. The network keeps it separate from unsupported oxidative cleavage chemistry and acknowledges thermal constraints on phenylalanine-related compounds (Yoo et al., 2013; Chen et al., 2014; Aspin et al., 2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of phenylalanine to styrene-forming decomposition branch", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "493-553K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "rapid decomposition window above phenylalanine s